   <titles>
      <title>Vectors Modeling Forces</title>
      <plain.title>Forces</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>When a force acts on an object, it does so in a certain direction and with a certain strength. Thus we can model a force by a vector. The direction in which the force acts corresponds to the direction of the vector, and the magnitude of the force corresponds to the length of the vector.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>For example, suppose a vector of length <math>
                     <latex>1</latex>
                  </math> corresponds to a force of <math>
                     <latex>1000N</latex>
                  </math>. Then the following arrows represent forces as 
			<subordinate>
                     <hot>indicated</hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Place your pointer over an arrow to get answers.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>.
			</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>vector</term>
                  <term>force</term>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/ForceArrows.gif" height="169" width="319">
                        <image.mapping>
                           <area shape="rect" coords="25,29,121,47">
                              <info>
                                 <info.caption>What does the red vector represent?</info.caption>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>This vector represents a force of <math>
                                          <latex>4000N</latex>
                                       </math> to the right.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="15,131,25,149,191,77,175,59">
                              <info>
                                 <info.caption>What does the green vector represent?</info.caption>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>This vector represents a force of <math>
                                          <latex>\sqrt{58} \cdot 1000N</latex>
                                       </math> directed to the upper right.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="189,31,285,105,301,87,209,15">
                              <info>
                                 <info.caption>What does the blue vector represent?</info.caption>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>This vector represents a force of <math>
                                          <latex>5000N</latex>
                                       </math> directed to the lower right</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                        </image.mapping>
                     </img>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>From experiments we learn that several forces acting simultaneously on an object can be consolidated into a single force. Moreover, the consolidated force corresponds to the vector sum of the individual forces. â€“ The picture below illustrates this. Here we have two forces, <math>
                     <latex>F_1</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>F_2</latex>
                  </math> acting on an object. The resulting combined force is described by the red vector <math>
                     <latex>F_1 + F_2</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/ForceSum.gif" height="173" width="391">
                        <image.mapping>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="11,97,27,109,285,41,259,23,21,89,21,91,21,97">
                              <info>
                                 <info.caption>What does the green vector represent?</info.caption>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>This vector represents the force vector <math>
                                          <latex>F_2</latex>
                                       </math> acting on the object, assumed to be at its tail.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="25,113,121,161,133,143,45,105">
                              <info>
                                 <info.caption>What does the blue vector represent?</info.caption>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>This vector represents the force vector <math>
                                          <latex>F_1</latex>
                                       </math> acting on the object, assumed to be at its tail.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="369,95,369,77,95,93,67,105">
                              <info>
                                 <info.caption>What does the red vector represent?</info.caption>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>This vector represents the single force that results from the combined actions of <math>
                                          <latex>F_1</latex>
                                       </math> and <math>
                                          <latex>F_2</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                        </image.mapping>
                     </img>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
